{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522292"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13818"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13818"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.22,0.4,0.09,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58487"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6435"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43903"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12711"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58487"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-day history of a right facial rash. He initially developed a blister-like rash and now reports severe pain in the associated area. There is no radiation of the pain, and he reports the lesions themselves as painful. He denies any changes in his vision. He has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis for which he takes methotrexate. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Examination reveals a vesicular rash on the right side of his forehead, extending down onto his nose with several open lesions. Fluorescein staining of the eye does not reveal any corneal involvement and his visual acuity is 6/6 in both eyes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is commenced on valaciclovir 1 g three times daily for seven days.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management of his pain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lignocaine 5% patches applied to affected area","Prednisolone 50 mg daily for seven days","Pregabalin 75 mg twice daily until pain resolves","Naproxen 500 mg twice daily for ten days","Gabapentin 300 mg three times daily until pain resolves"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EShingles can commonly cause both severe nociceptive and neuropathic pain, particularly if it is on the face. Nociceptive pain is typically described as sharp, aching, or throbbing and is often associated with tissue damage or inflammation, as seen in this patient\u0027s vesicular rash. In contrast, neuropathic pain is often described as burning, tingling, or shooting and may occur in the absence of visible lesions. Identifying these characteristics can help guide appropriate pain management strategies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient\u0027s pain is described as severe and associated with the vesicular lesions, indicating nociceptive pain due to the inflammation and tissue damage from the rash. There is no mention of burning, tingling, or shooting pain, which are characteristic of neuropathic pain, suggesting that the pain is primarily nociceptive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntiviral treatment should be initiated in the first 72 hours as this provides the greatest benefit; however, in immunocompromised patients, it should be initiated at any stage of the disease process. Prompt initiation of antiviral treatment accelerates pain resolution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor severe shingles pain, it is recommended to initiate \u003Cstrong\u003Eprednisolone 50 mg daily for seven days\u003C/strong\u003E to reduce nociceptive pain, and therefore this is the correct answer. Large studies have shown that pain resolves faster when prednisolone is used, especially when used in combination with an antiviral (such as valaciclovir). As prednisolone is used for only seven days, it does not require a dose tapering.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMild nociceptive shingles pain can be treated with a combination of NSAIDs \u003Cstrong\u003E(such as naproxen 500 mg twice daily for ten days)\u003C/strong\u003E and paracetamol. However, this patient reports severe pain affecting his quality of life; therefore, oral prednisolone would be the more appropriate answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELignocaine 5% patches\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to treat neuropathic shingles pain; however, they cannot be used on broken skin or lesions, which are common in the acute phase of infection. In this patient, examination revealed active vesicles and skin breakdown, which would mean lignocaine would be contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGabapentinoids such as \u003Cstrong\u003EPregabalin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EGabapentin\u003C/strong\u003E can also be utilised in neuropathic pain related to shingles. However, in this stem, there are no features in the history to clearly suggest a neuropathic component to the patient\u0027s pain. Gabapentinoids can be used in addition to prednisolone if there is concurrent nociceptive and neuropathic pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Moderate to severe nociceptive pain in shingles should be promptly treated with a course of oral prednisolone.","Antiviral treatment should be initiated within 72 hours; however, it is recommended at any stage in patients who are immunosuppressed.","Early commencement of antiviral treatment accelerates pain resolution."],"references":["Stankus SJ, Dlugopolski M, Packer D. Management of Herpes Zoster (Shingles) and Postherpetic Neuralgia. American Family Physician [Internet]. 2000 Apr 15;61(8):2437\u201344. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2000/0415/p2437.html/1000","Saguil A, Kane S, Mercado M, Lauters R. Herpes Zoster and Postherpetic Neuralgia: Prevention and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2017 Nov 15;96(10):656-663. PMID: 29431387.","Nicholson B. Differential diagnosis: nociceptive and neuropathic pain. Am J Manag Care. 2006 Jun;12(9 Suppl):S256-62. PMID: 16774457.","St John Smith E. Advances in understanding nociception and neuropathic pain. J Neurol. 2018 Feb;265(2):231-238. doi: 10.1007/s00415-017-8641-6. Epub 2017 Oct 14. PMID: 29032407; PMCID: PMC5808094."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43903"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43903"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-01T10:33:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-01T11:08:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6435"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58487"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"